# Lymphatic System

> The lymphatic system is a **one-way drainage network** of vessels, nodes, and organs that returns interstitial fluid to the bloodstream, absorbs dietary fat (lacteals), and mediates **immune surveillance**. It is the anatomical basis of the immune system.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[00 - AnatomyLink Home]]
- Drains into: Venous system at left subclavian vein (thoracic duct) and right subclavian vein (right lymphatic duct)
- Closely related: [[Circulatory System]] (parallel drainage), [[Digestive System]] (lacteals absorb fat)
- Important in: [[Reproductive System]] (gonadal lymphatics to para-aortic nodes), [[Urinary System]], all organ systems

## 🗂️ Components

| Structure | Function |
|-----------|----------|
| [[Lymph Nodes]] | Filter lymph; immune cell activation (B and T cells) |
| [[Spleen]] | Filters blood; removes old RBCs; immune reservoir |
| [[Thymus]] | T-cell maturation (most active in childhood) |
| [[Tonsils]] | Mucosal immune defence (Waldeyer's ring) |
| Lymphatic vessels | Transport lymph from periphery to thoracic duct/right lymphatic duct |
| Bone marrow | Lymphocyte production (B-cell maturation) |

## 🔑 Thoracic Duct vs. Right Lymphatic Duct

| | Thoracic Duct | Right Lymphatic Duct |
|-|---------------|---------------------|
| Origin | Cisterna chyli (L1–L2) | Junction of right jugular + subclavian lymphatic trunks |
| Drains | Lower limbs, abdomen, left thorax, left head/neck, left arm (~¾ body) | Right head/neck, right arm, right thorax (~¼ body) |
| Terminates | Left subclavian vein (venous angle) | Right subclavian vein |

## 🏥 Key Clinical Conditions
- **Lymphadenopathy** — enlarged nodes; reactive (infection), malignant (lymphoma, metastasis)
- **Lymphoma** — Hodgkin's (Reed-Sternberg cells, good prognosis) vs. Non-Hodgkin's
- **Lymphoedema** — primary (Milroy's) or secondary (post-surgery/radiation/filariasis); pitting oedema
- **HIV/AIDS** — CD4+ T-cell depletion; opportunistic infections
- **Sentinel node biopsy** — first draining node from tumour; guides staging (breast cancer, melanoma)

